Introduction to logistic regression¶

Regression is concerned with predicting a continuous response. Classification on the other hand, is interested with classifying a categorical variable. Binary classification is focused on classifying an outcome into one of two possible categories. This notebook introduces binary classification with logistic regression, a type of generalized linear model (GLM). It stress the similarities with and key difference with Linear Models.

Binary classification with logistic regression is introduced in this notebook using a real data example that had serious consequences. We will work the Space Shuttle Challenger data set. If you are not familiar with Space Shuttle Challenger, the vehicle exploded mid launch on a cold January morning in 1986 due to an O-ring failure. All 7 astronauts on board died.

A data set exists that consists of previous O-ring damage events, as well as the ambient (outside) air temperature. In this notebook, we will introduce logistic regression mostly focusing on fitting the model and predicting the failure probability.

Binary outcomes¶

The response, y, is a binary variable. It can take on just one of two possible states. However, we have encoded the variable to be an integer, 0 or 1. The value of 1 corresponds to a failure event, and the value of 0 represents the failure did not happen. The 0/1 encoding allows us to work with any generic binary outcome, such as Hit/Out, Pass/Fail, True/False, Positive/Negative, etc... We can think of it as we observed 1 event or we saw 0 events. The total number of events is the sum of y since we are summing together 0's and 1's (a zero does not contribute to the count).

When building a classifier, it is important to consider the empirical or observed proportion of events. We can calculate that simply as the number of events out of the total number of observations. The empirical fraction can be calculated simply using the .mean() method since the mean is the sum (of 0's and 1's) divided by the number of observations.

Logistic regression¶

Binary classifiers classify observations into one of two possible categories. With our current applications those states are either fail, y=1, or non-failure, y=0. Most binary classifiers however do not model or directly classify the outcome. Most binary classifiers predict the probability of the event. We learned in CMPINF 2100 that the classification occurs by comparing the predicted probability to a threshold! However, that is the not the point of the current example. This example dives deeper into the inner workings of the logistic regression.

Predicting or modeling a probability is challenging. We cannot use standard regression techniques that we discussed with the linear model. A probability value is bounded between 0 and 1 (it is a fraction). We cannot have a probability of 2 or a probability of -1.5. Thus, we cannot simply use the linear relationship we introduced with regression:

$$ \mu_n = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times x_{n} $$

Instead, we need to perform a transformation. Specifically, we will use the logit transformation which places the model on the log odds ratio rather than the probability directly:

$$ \mathrm{logodds}_n = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times x_n $$

The log odds ratio is the natural log of the odds ratio. The odds ratio (OR) is defined as the probability divided by 1 minus the probability.:

$$ \mathrm{OR} = \frac{ \mathrm{Probability} }{1 - \mathrm{Probability} } $$

Thus, the model we will work with states that the log-odds ratio is a function of the input.

$$ \log \left(\frac{\mathrm{Probability}_n}{1 - \mathrm{Probability}_n } \right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times x_n$$

The log-odds is also know as the logit function. The model is typically named for the inverse or reciprical operation, the logistic. Thus, logistic regression gets its name because we are placing a regression model on the log-odds ratio of a binary outcome. The application of logistic regression is for classifying a binary outcome. Therefore, even though logistic regression as the term regression in its name it is not used for predicting continuous outputs!

Model fitting: Likelihood and Loss function¶

Although the formulation is different from linear regression, we will still estimate the coefficients (the intercept and slope) by minimizing the error. The formulation of the ERROR is typically referred to as the LOSS function. Alternatively, we can view model fitting as maximizing the LIKELIHOOD. We learned with linear models that maximizing the likelihood is equivalent to minimizing the sum of squared errors. The same concept applies to classification except the loss function (sum of squared errors) and thus the probability distribution associated with the likelihood are different! Therefore, the Gaussian likelihood is not used for binary classification!

Conceptually, we want the loss or error in classification to represent "consistency" between the predicted probabilities and the observed events. If the model predicts a high event probability we hope to observe the event much more frequently than the non-event. Conversely, if the model predicts a low probability we hope to the event is rarely observed. Thus, if the model predicts the event will occur with 80% probability, and yet we routinely do not observe the event, such misclassifications will result in poor model performance.

These conceptual goals are represented by the Bernoulli distribution. The Bernoulli is a discrete distribution that calculates the probability of the event. The LIKELIHOOD is therefore the probability of observing the binary outcome, $y$, GIVEN the event probability.

$$ p\left(y \mid \mathrm{Probability}\right) = \mathrm{Bernoulli}\left(y \mid \mathrm{Probability} \right)$$

The Bernoulli distribution is written out as:

$$ \mathrm{Bernoulli}\left(y \mid \mathrm{Probability} \right) = \mathrm{Probability}^{y} \left(1 - \mathrm{Probability}\right)^{1-y}$$

Thus, if we know the event probability, we can calculate how LIKELY an event could be.

As discussed in the regression portion, we can assume observations are conditionally independent if we know the event probability. All remaining variation is random. Thus, the event probability serves the same role as the average output in the regresssion! This allows us to consider numerous observations of the binary outcome. The "complete" likelihood is the product of $N$ conditionally independent observations:

$$ \mathrm{LIKELIHOOD} = \prod_{n=1}^{N} \left( \mathrm{Bernoulli} \left(y_n \mid \mathrm{Probability}_n \right) \right) = \prod_{n=1}^{N} \left( \mathrm{Probability}_{n}^{y_n} \left(1 - \mathrm{Probability}_n\right)^{1-y_n} \right)$$

The event probability is a function of the inputs and includes unknown coefficients that must be estimated by maximizing the likelihood. The likelihood is maximized by first applying the natural log which thus provides the log-likelihood function as the sum of $N$ conditionally independent log-Bernoulli distributions:

$$ \log \left[ \mathrm{LIKELIHOOD} \right] = \sum_{n=1}^{N} \left( \log \left[\mathrm{Bernoulli}\left(y_n \mid \mathrm{Probability}_n \right) \right] \right) $$

Each observation's likelihood can be simplified through the properties of log-arithmetic. The log-likelihood for a single observation is:

$$ \log \left[\mathrm{Bernoulli}\left(y_n \mid \mathrm{Probability}_n \right) \right] = y_n \log \left[\mathrm{Probability}_n \right] + \left(1 - y_n\right) \log \left[ 1 - \mathrm{Probability}_n \right] $$

The above expression might be daunting to look at, but it is conceptual simple to understand. In words the a single observation's log-likelihood is the outcome value (1 or 0) multiplied by the probability of the outcome. Essentially, there are 2 classes - event ($y=1$) or non-event ($y=0$). The probability of each class is $\mathrm{Probability}$ for the event and $1-\mathrm{Probability}$ for the non-event.

The unknown regression coefficients, $\beta$, of the function for the probability, $\mathrm{Probability}=f\left(x, \beta\right)$, are estimated to maximize the log-likelihood.

However, as previously mentioned we could also think of fitting the model by minimizing a loss function. The loss function for binary classification is equal to the negative log-likelihood!

$$ \mathrm{LOSS} = - \log \left[ \mathrm{LIKELIHOOD} \right] $$

Binary classification problems give a special name to the loss function. It is known as cross-entropy. Thus, fitting the classifier by minimizing the cross-entropy (CE) is the same thing as maximizing the Bernoulli likelihood function!!

$$ \mathrm{CE} = - \sum_{n=1}^{N} \left( \log \left[\mathrm{Bernoulli}\left(y_n \mid \mathrm{Probability}_n \right) \right] \right) = - \sum_{n=1}^{N} \left( y_n \log \left[\mathrm{Probability}_n \right] + \left(1 - y_n\right) \log \left[ 1 - \mathrm{Probability}_n \right] \right)$$

Link and Inverse link function¶

The event probability is a function of the input. However, as previously discussed the probability is not modeled directly. Instead the "regression model" is applied to the log-odds ratio. The log-odds ratio or logit function is known as the link between the Probability and the linear predictor. We can recover the Probability by inverting the link function. The inverse of the logit is the logistic function. The Probability is therefore calculated by applying the logistic function to the log-odds ratio:

$$\mathrm{Probability} = \mathrm{logit}^{-1} \left( \mathrm{logodds} \right) $$

The $\mathrm{logodds}$ is the linear predictor which is linearly related to the unknown regression coefficients.

Modeling Space Shuttle application¶

Let's return to modeling the Space Shuttle data. We wish to model the log-odds ratio of the O-ring failure with respect to the ambient temperature. Thus we want a linear predictor of the form shown below:

$$ \log \left(\frac{\mathrm{Probability}}{1 - \mathrm{Probability} } \right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times \mathrm{Temperature}$$

The unknown coefficients we must learn are the intercept and slope applied to the input Temperature. However, rather than working Temperature directly we will first standardize the variable by subtracting out the mean and dividing by the standard deviation. We are therefore preprocessing the input before the model. The cell below manually performs the standardization because it is simple in this application. You are of course free to use StandardScaler() and Pipelines to manage the preprocessing for you. However in this notebook we will calculate the standardized temperature manually as a reminder for what StandardScaler() is doing.

Create a new column, x, which represents the standardized version of the temperature.

In [18]:
df['x'] = (df['Temperature'] - df.Temperature.mean()) / df.Temperature.std()

We will use statsmodels to fit the logistic regression model. The syntax is very similar to the regression case, except we need to use a different function comapred to regression. Instead of using smf.ols() we must use the smf.logit() method. The rest of the syntax is the same. We need to specify the model of interest with the formula interface. The cell initializes the model as a linear relationship between the log-odds ratio and the input.

Remember that the smf formula methods require the model to be initialized and then "fit". Notice below that the logistic regression model is the smf.logit() method.

In [21]:
def my_coefplot(model_object, figsize_use=(10, 5)):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize_use)
    
    ax.errorbar(y = model_object.params.index,
               x = model_object.params,
               fmt = 'o', color = 'steelblue', ecolor='steelblue',
               xerr = 2 * model_object.bse,
               elinewidth = 3, ms=10)
    
    ax.axvline(x = 0, linestyle='--', linewidth=5, color='grey')
    
    ax.set_xlabel('coefficient value')
    
    plt.show()

Prediction¶

The slope on the x variable is negative and thus the log-odds ratio will decrease as the input increases. However, it is very important to remember that the model is on the log-odds ratio and thus the log-odds will decrease on average 1.64 units for every 1 unit increase of the standardized input. Thus, the slope does not tell us how the probability will directly change as the input changes. The slopes correspond to changes to the log-odds ratio. However, if log-odds decreases then probability decreases! If log-odds increases then probability increases!

Let's make predictions to understand the behavior in the model. Rather than predicting the training set, let's make a very fine resolution grid and predict the event probability (y=1 with respect to the standardized temperature.

What not to do...¶

We discussed several times in CMPINF 2100 that we should NEVER use a regression model for binary classification. We might be tempted to do so because the output has been encoded as 0 or 1. However, regression assumes a Gaussian Likelihood. The regression problem "thinks" the outcome can be any continuous number. A Gaussian is not appropriate when the output is binary!

Let's fit such a model just to show how it leads to incorrect interpretations. No warnings are provided when we call smf.ols(). The smf.ols() function does not realize it is working on a binary classification problem! All it knows is that the output is a numeric variable!

In [32]:
wrong_fit = smf.ols(formula = 'y ~ x', data = df).fit()

The correct logistic regression model does not suffer from such issues. The logit transformation makes sure the predicted probability is always between 0 and 1. The logit transformation (and its inverse the logistic) create an S-shaped curve which causes the predicted probability to come close to but never exceed 1 and come close to but never drop below 0.

ax.set_xlabel('standardized temperature, x')
ax.set_ylabel('binary outcome, y')
ax.set_title('Predictions from incorrectly trained Regression Model')

plt.show()

Summary¶

This report demonstrated the two major differences between Linear Models for regression and Logistic Regression models for Classification. It showed that the Gaussian likelihood is not appropriate because the output is binary and not continuous. It also showed that the logit transformation is critical for ensuring the predicted probability is bounded between 0 and 1! Both aspects are critically important in order to properly apply and interpret binary classifiers!
